Certainly! I can provide you with an example of a simple calculator implementation using both Python and C language.

Python:
Here's an example of a basic calculator implementation in Python using the Tkinter GUI toolkit:

```python
import tkinter as tk

def calculate():
    try:
        result = eval(expression.get())
        output_label.configure(text="Result: " + str(result))
    except:
        output_label.configure(text="Invalid Expression")

root = tk.Tk()
root.title("Calculator")

expression = tk.StringVar()

input_entry = tk.Entry(root, textvariable=expression)
input_entry.pack()

calculate_button = tk.Button(root, text="Calculate", command=calculate)
calculate_button.pack()

output_label = tk.Label(root)
output_label.pack()

root.mainloop()
```

Save the code in a file called `calculator.py` and run it using the command `python3 calculator.py`. The GUI window will appear, and you can enter mathematical expressions in the input field and click the "Calculate" button to see the result displayed.

C:
Here's an example of a simple calculator implementation in C language using the GTK+ library:

```c
#include <gtk/gtk.h>

GtkBuilder *builder;
GtkWidget *input_entry;
GtkWidget *output_label;

static void calculate(GtkButton *button, gpointer user_data)
{
    gchar *expression = gtk_entry_get_text(GTK_ENTRY(input_entry));
    gint result;

    if (g_strcmp0(expression, "") != 0)
    {
        if (g_str_has_prefix(expression, "0x"))
            sscanf(expression, "%i", &result);
        else
            result = eval(expression);

        gchar result_text[50];
        g_snprintf(result_text, sizeof(result_text), "Result: %d", result);
        gtk_label_set_text(GTK_LABEL(output_label), result_text);
    }
    else
        gtk_label_set_text(GTK_LABEL(output_label), "Invalid Expression");
}

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    gtk_init(&argc, &argv);

    builder = gtk_builder_new_from_file("calculator.glade");
    GtkWidget *window = GTK_WIDGET(gtk_builder_get_object(builder, "window"));

    input_entry = GTK_WIDGET(gtk_builder_get_object(builder, "input_entry"));
    output_label = GTK_WIDGET(gtk_builder_get_object(builder, "output_label"));

    gtk_builder_connect_signals(builder, NULL);

    gtk_widget_show(window);

    gtk_main();

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, you need to create a file called `calculator.c`, and for the GUI layout, you can use the Glade UI designer to design the calculator window and save it in a file called `calculator.glade`. Ensure that you have the GTK+ development libraries installed on your system and then compile the code using the GCC compiler with the command `gcc -o calculator calculator.c $(pkg-config --cflags --libs gtk+-3.0)`. This will generate an executable called `calculator`, which you can run to open the calculator window.

Please note that the C implementation requires more code due to the nature of the language, including dealing with signals and callbacks.
